{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17633077","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17633077"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:48:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:48:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17461"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17461","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17461"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10151"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70874"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10151","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10151"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17461"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56341"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5398"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23751"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23822"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70874","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70874"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EEpidemiologists often use different measures to describe survival in patient populations.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes relative survival?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Survival adjusted for patient age only","Time until 50% of patients have died","Percentage of patients alive at a specific time point","Survival time from diagnosis to death","Observed survival divided by expected survival in the general population"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERelative survival is calculated by dividing the observed survival in a patient group by the expected survival in the general population\u003C/strong\u003E. This measure accounts for background mortality rates and allows comparison between different populations and time periods.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurvival adjusted for patient age only\u003C/strong\u003E describes an incomplete adjustment that fails to account for other important background mortality factors in the general population.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETime until 50% of patients have died\u003C/strong\u003E describes median survival time, which is a different measure that does not consider expected survival in the general population.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPercentage of patients alive at a specific time point\u003C/strong\u003E describes a crude survival rate that does not account for expected mortality in matched populations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurvival time from diagnosis to death\u003C/strong\u003E describes overall survival, which measures absolute survival time without reference to population expectations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERelative survival is particularly useful in cancer epidemiology as it helps determine excess mortality attributable to the disease. Values can exceed 100% if the patient group survives better than the general population, such as in cases where patients adopt healthier behaviours after diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Relative survival compares observed survival in a patient group to expected survival in the general population.","Relative survival is expressed as a ratio or percentage and can exceed 100% if patients survive better than the general population.","Relative survival accounts for background mortality rates and is commonly used in cancer epidemiology."],"references":["Shultz JM, Sullivan LM, Galea S. Public Health: An Introduction to the Science and Practice of Population Health. Springer Publishing Company; 2021.","Ray, Sumantra, and others (eds), Oxford Handbook of Clinical and Healthcare Research, 1, Oxford Medical Handbooks (Oxford, 2016; online edn, Oxford Academic, 1 Mar. 2016), https://doi.org/10.1093/med/9780199608478.001.0001"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56341"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17461"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56341","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56341"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T14:53:33+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T14:54:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10151"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70874"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":